analysisWe need solve Futoshiki 6x6 with given clues and inequalities. Let's solve logically or brute force mentally? Might be easier to brute force mentally? Let's attempt.

We have 6x6 Latin square with numbers 1-6 each row/col.

Given grid:

Row1: [1, _, 4, _, _, _]
Row2: [_, _, _, 1, _, _]
Row3: [_, _, _, _, 1, 3]
Row4: [_, _, _, _, _, _]
Row5: [_, _, 1, _, _, 5]
Row6: [5, 2, 6, _, _, _]

Inequalities:

(1,2) < (2,2)
(1,3) > (2,3)
(1,5) < (2,5)
(2,5) < (2,6)

Indices 1-based.

Let's denote cells.

Row1 col2 < Row2 col2.

Row1 col3 > Row2 col3.

Row1 col5 < Row2 col5.

Row2 col5 < Row2 col6.

We need fill all.

Let's try solving.

Row1 currently has numbers 1,4. Missing {2,3,5,6}. Col constraints.

- R1C2: column2 currently has: R1C2 ?, R2C2 ?, R3C2 ?, R4C2 ?, R5C2 ?, R6C2=2. So missing {1,3,4,5,6}. But 1 already used in row1, so {3,5,6}. Also inequality: R1C2 < R2C2. So R1C2 less than R2C2.

- R1C4: column4 values: R1C4 ?, R2C4=1, R3C4 ?, R4C4 ?, R5C4 ?, R6C4 ?. Missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Row1 missing {2,3,5,6}. So R1C4 ∈ {2,3,5,6}.

- R1C5: column5 values: R1C5 ?, R2C5 ?, R3C5=1, R4C5 ?, R5C5 ?, R6C5 ?. Missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Row1 missing {2,3,5,6}. Also inequality: R1C5 < R2C5. So R1C5 less than R2C5.

- R1C6: column6 values: R1C6 ?, R2C6 ?, R3C6=3, R4C6 ?, R5C6=5, R6C6 ?. Missing {1,2,4,6}. Row1 missing {2,3,5,6} -> intersection {2,6}. So R1C6 ∈ {2,6}.

Row2: [_, _, _, 1, _, _] missing {2,3,4,5,6}. 
- R2C1 column1: values R1C1=1, R2C1 ?, R3C1 ?, R4C1 ?, R5C1 ?, R6C1=5. Missing {2,3,4,6}. So R2C1 ∈ {2,3,4,6}.

- R2C2 column2 missing {1,3,4,5,6}. Row2 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Intersection {3,4,5,6}. Also inequality: R1C2 < R2C2. So R2C2 greater than R1C2.

- R2C3 column3 values: R1C3=4, R2C3 ?, R3C3 ?, R4C3 ?, R5C3=1, R6C3=6. Missing {2,3,5}. Row2 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Intersection {2,3,5}. Also inequality: R1C3 > R2C3, so R2C3 < 4. So R2C3 ∈ {2,3}. (5 would be >4, not allowed). So {2,3}.

- R2C5 column5 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Row2 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. So any. Inequality: R1C5 < R2C5. Also R2C5 < R2C6.

- R2C6 column6 missing {1,2,4,6}. Row2 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Intersection {2,4,6}. Also inequality: R2C5 < R2C6.

Row3: [_, _, _, _, 1, 3] missing {2,4,5,6}. 
- R3C1 column1 missing {2,3,4,6}. Row3 missing {2,4,5,6} -> {2,4,6}.

- R3C2 column2 missing {1,3,4,5,6}. Row3 missing {2,4,5,6} -> {4,5,6}.

- R3C3 column3 missing {2,3,5}. Row3 missing {2,4,5,6} -> {2,5}.

- R3C4 column4 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Row3 missing {2,4,5,6} -> {2,4,5,6}.

Row4: all empty [_,_,_,_,_,_] missing {1,2,3,4,5,6}.

Row5: [_, _, 1, _, _, 5] missing {2,3,4,6}. 
- R5C1 column1 missing {2,3,4,6}. -> {2,3,4,6}
- R5C2 column2 missing {1,3,4,5,6}. -> {3,4,6}
- R5C4 column4 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. -> {2,3,4,6}
- R5C5 column5 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. -> {2,3,4,6}

Row6: [5,2,6,_,_,_] missing {1,3,4}. 
- R6C4 column4 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. -> {3,4}
- R6C5 column5 missing {2,3,4,5,6}. -> {3,4}
- R6C6 column6 missing {1,2,4,6}. -> {1,4}

Now we can try solving systematically.

Consider column constraints.

Column1: values: R1=1, R2=?, R3=?, R4=?, R5=?, R6=5. Missing {2,3,4,6}. Candidates:
- R2C1 {2,3,4,6}
- R3C1 {2,4,6}
- R4C1 {1-6} -> {2,3,4,6}
- R5C1 {2,3,4,6}
Only number 3 appears in many. No singles.

Column2: values: R1=?, R2=?, R3=?, R4=?, R5=?, R6=2. Missing {1,3,4,5,6}. Candidates:
- R1C2 {3,5,6}
- R2C2 {3,4,5,6}
- R3C2 {4,5,6}
- R4C2 {1-6}->{1,3,4,5,6}
- R5C2 {3,4,6}
Only number1 appears only in R4C2 maybe? Wait R4C2 includes 1. Others don't have 1. So R4C2 must be 1. Good.

So R4C2 = 1.

Update row4 now missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Column2 solved.

Column3: values: R1=4, R2=?, R3=?, R4=?, R5=1, R6=6. Missing {2,3,5}. Candidates:
- R2C3 {2,3}
- R3C3 {2,5}
- R4C3 {2,3,5}
Only number5 appears in R3C3 or R4C3. Not single.

Column4: values: R1=?, R2=1, R3=?, R4=?, R5=?, R6=?. Missing {2,3,4,5,6}. Candidates:
- R1C4 {2,3,5,6}
- R3C4 {2,4,5,6}
- R4C4 {2,3,4,5,6}
- R5C4 {2,3,4,6}
- R6C4 {3,4}
Only number? 6 appears in R1C4,R3C4,R4C4. 5 appears R1C4,R3C4,R4C4
